<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>
  
<exercise label="mcq-sep-1">
  <title>Recognizing a Separable Equation</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Which of the following differential equations is separable?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = x(1+y^2)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. This can be written as 
          <m>\frac{dy}{1+y^2} = x\,dx</m>,  
          which separates <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = x + y</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Not separable; the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> terms cannot be isolated into 
          separate factors.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = \sin(x+y)</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Not separable because <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are entangled inside one function.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcq-sep-2">
  <title>Identifying the Separation Step</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      To solve <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = y e^x</m>, which of the following is the correct next step?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{y}\,dy = e^x\,dx</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. This isolates <m>y</m> terms on one side and <m>x</m> terms on the other—exactly the method used in separable equations.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\displaystyle dy = ye^{x}\,dx</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No separation has occurred yet.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\displaystyle dy = e^{xy}\,dx</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>This changes the equation incorrectly.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcq-sep-3">
  <title>Solving a Simple Separable Equation</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Solve the separable equation <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = 3y</m>.  
      What is the general solution?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>y = Ce^{3x}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Separating gives <m>\frac{1}{y}dy = 3\,dx</m>; integrating yields 
          <m>\ln|y| = 3x + C</m>, so <m>y=Ce^{3x}</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = 3e^x</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>The exponent must be <m>3x</m>, and a constant factor must remain arbitrary.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = Cx^3</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No, that would satisfy <m>y' = 3Cx^2</m>, not <m>3y</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcq-sep-4">
  <title>Solving With an Initial Condition</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Solve the IVP  
      <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = x^2 y,\qquad y(0)=2.</m>  
      What is <m>y(x)</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>y = 2\, e^{x^{3}/3}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Separation gives <m>\frac{1}{y}dy = x^2 dx</m>.  
          Integrating: <m>\ln|y| = x^3/3 + C</m>.  
          Applying <m>y(0)=2</m> gives <m>C=\ln 2</m>, so  
          <m>y = 2 e^{x^3/3}</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = 2e^{x^{2}/2}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Incorrect exponent; integrate <m>x^2</m> carefully.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = 2 + x^3/3</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—this would satisfy <m>y' = x^2/1</m>, missing the factor of <m>y</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcq-sep-5">
  <title>Conceptual Meaning of Separation</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Why is separating variables a valid method for solving  
      <m>\frac{dy}{dx}=f(x)g(y)</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>Because we can treat <m>dy/dx</m> like a fraction and rearrange to <m>\frac{1}{g(y)}dy = f(x)dx</m>, then integrate both sides.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Separate all <m>y</m>-terms on one side 
          and all <m>x</m>-terms on the other, then integrate.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Because any differential equation can always be separated.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—many important ODEs are not separable.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Because separation avoids integration entirely.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—integrating both sides is the essential step.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>
   
<exercise>
<statement>
<p>
 Solve the initial value problem <me>\frac{dy}{dx} = -6xy, \ \ y(0) = -4.</me>  Hint: 'Separate' the variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> by, informally, writing the equation as <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{y} = -6x \ dx.</m>
</p>  
</statement>

<solution>
  <p>
    We begin with the separable differential equation
    <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = -6xy.</m>
    To separate variables, we (informally) rewrite this as
    <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{y}\,dy = -6x\,dx.</m>
  </p>

  <p>
    Integrate both sides:
  </p>

  <me>
    \int \frac{1}{y}\,dy = \int -6x\,dx.
  </me>

  <p>
    This yields
  </p>

  <me>
    \ln|y| = -3x^{2} + C.
  </me>

  <p>
    Exponentiating gives the general solution
  </p>

  <me>
    y = C e^{-3x^{2}}.
  </me>

  <p>
    Now apply the initial condition <m>y(0) = -4</m>:
  </p>

  <me>
    -4 = C e^{0} = C.
  </me>

  <p>
    Therefore the particular solution is
  </p>

  <me>
    y(x) = -4\, e^{-3x^{2}}.
  </me>
</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <statement>
<p> Consider the ODE <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} =-6xy</m>.  Using separation of variables, we earlier found a general solution to be <m>y(x) = Ce^{-3x^2}</m>.  Hence, the IVP <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} =-6xy; y(0)=-4</m> has unique solution <m>y(x) = -4e^{-3x^2}</m>. 
</p> 
<ol>
<li><p> What is the unique solution to the following IVP? <me>\frac{dy}{dx} =-6xy; y(0)=0</me> </p></li>
<li><p> Why does the method of separation of variables `lose' the solution found in (a)?  </p></li>
</ol>
</statement>

<solution>

  <p>
    We are told that the differential equation
    <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = -6xy</m>
    has the general solution
    <m>y(x) = C e^{-3x^{2}}.</m>
  </p>

  <ol>

    <li>
      <p>
        To solve the IVP
        <me>
          \frac{dy}{dx} = -6xy, \qquad y(0)=0,
        </me>
        substitute <m>x=0</m> into the general solution:
      </p>

      <me>
        y(0) = C e^{-3\cdot 0^{2}} = C.
      </me>

      <p>
        Since <m>y(0)=0</m>, it follows that <m>C=0</m>.  
        Therefore the unique solution to the IVP is
      </p>

      <me>
        y(x) \equiv 0.
      </me>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        In the separation‑of‑variables method, we informally write
        <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = -6xy</m> as
      </p>

      <me>
        \frac{1}{y}\,dy = -6x\,dx.
      </me>

      <p>
        This step requires dividing by <m>y</m>.  
        When <m>y=0</m>, this division is not valid.  
        Because the constant‑zero function <m>y(x)\equiv 0</m> satisfies the ODE but
        makes <m>\tfrac{1}{y}</m> undefined, the separation process
        <em>loses</em> this solution.  
        Thus the algebraic manipulation excludes the zero solution even though it is a
        perfectly valid solution of the original differential equation.
      </p>
    </li>

  </ol>

</solution>
</exercise>


